deck_excerpt: Swarm the Board with Level 1 Monsters to XYZ some big boys
deck_description:
Overarching Info

 

Vague Strategy:

For starters, the main strategy is to dump as many Lv.1's as possible on the board early to go into F0:Utopic Draco Future.

If you brick, then attempt to churn through the deck Magical Mallet or Card Destruction while leveraging the defensive cards to set up a board with more favorable conditions.

Sometimes though, you will get lucky and draw into some cards that facilitate the deck's gimmicks (Dystopia, Number 99: Utopic Dragon, Rank-up-Magic: The Seventh, AA-Zeus, etc.)

 

Most Notable Lv.1 monsters:

Jester Confit, Turbo Booster, and Big One Warrior are free (for the most part) special summons.

Kinka-byo is basically the only monster you want to normal summon if you have to.

Evil Thorn can be a great extender alongside Kinka-byo; and also a uniquely optimal One for One target. 

 

Treeborn Frog is Treeborn Frog; dump it in the GY with either foolish burial or Big One Warrior.

 

Boss Monsters:

'Dystopia the Despondent': A big beater, not that difficult to summon with the board swarm.

'Number 99: Utopic Dragon' + 'Number 99: Utopia Dragonar': Some signifigant beaters, only these one is reliant on any Rank-up-magic. First summon Utopia Roots then use a Rank-up-magic to bring out one of the Number 99's.

'F0: Utopic Draco Future': This is a retrain of the original F0 and is not reliant on a Rank-up-magic; this is brought out with the two Slacker Magician XYZs, next summon F0:Utopic Future, lastly bring out F0:Utopic Draco Future.

'Full Armored Crystalzero Lancer': This is more of a support piece for shutting down effect monsters as it is reliant on Rank-up-magic The Seventh; use that to summon Regular Number 101, then C101, the summon Full Armored Crystal Zero Lancer on top of C101.

'Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder': This guy is just mean. If you swarm the board, go into the Lyralusc XYZ, and then attack directly to satisfy the conditions to bring out AA-Zeus.

 

Categorizing the Main Deck:

 

Openers: 3x Big One Warrior, 3x Kinka-byo, 3x Evil Thorn, 3x Where Arf Thou?

 

Extenders: 3x Turbo Booster, 3x Jester Confit, 2x Jack in the Hand, 1x Instant Fusion, 1x Scapeghost, 1x Scapegoat, 1x One Day of Peace, 1x One for One, 1x Monster Reborn, 1x Card Destruction, 2x Magical Mallet, 1x Foolish Burial, 1x Treeborn Frog

 

Defensive Cards: 1x Ghostrick Dullahan, 3x Battle Fader, 1x Vijam, 1x Rainbow Kuriboh

 

Non-Engine Reqs: 2x Hyper Rank-up Magic: Utopiaforce

 

Mid/Late-game Bombs: 1x Rank-up Magic: The Seventh One, 1x Dystopia the Despondent

 

 

Categorizing the Extra Deck:

 

Instant Fusion Target: 1x Thousand-eyes Restrict

 

'Rank-up Magic: The Seventh One’ Targets: start with 1x No.101: Silent Honor Ark, into 1x No.C101: Silent Honor DARK, finishing with 1x Full Armored CRYSTALZERO Lancer

 

Rank 1 # XYZ + ‘Rank-up Magic’ Targets: start with 1x No. 39 Utopia Roots, finish with 1x No.99: Utopia Dragonar + 1x No.99: Utopic Dragon

 

Generic Rank 1 XYZ: Start with two of the following (1x Slacker Magician, 1x Ghostrick Dullahan, 1x Sylvan Princess), go into 1x F0: Utopic Future, finish with 1x F0: Utopic Draco Future

 

5 Materials on Field: start with 1x Assembled Nightingale, finish with 1x AA-Zeus

 

 

Notes:

I plan to eventually add in a 'combos' section

I will modify the deck/extra deck/side deck over time into a more refined form

Any suggestions, constructive or otherwise, are appreciated

 

Change log:

- 2x Rank-up-Magic: Argent Chaos Force, + 2x Hyper Rank-up-Magic: Utopiaforce

- 1x No.99: Utopic Dragon, + No.99: Utopia Dragonar

deck_excerpt: My personal deck to climb Masterduel Ladder for maximum rank - Spright Runick!
deck_description:
Second only to Ishizu Tearlaments, Spright Runick is arguably still the current reigning champion of Masterduel meta as of September 2023. 

Another great incentive to pilot this deck right now is that it is the strongest strategy that makes amazing use of I:P Masquerena! So if you pulled her recently released alternate art, then I highly recommend playing Spright Runick so you can watch her glorious animation again and again!
 
The ridiculously strong combination of Spright and Runick's smothering control and endless grind game create a deck that all strategies would have to fear and respect. Sprights ending on 3-5 interruptions (Sprind's bounce, Red's monster negate, Carrot's S/T negate, Smasher's banish, and I:P Masquerena's quick link) combined with Runick's draw 3 and multiple quick play spells generally stop any deck cold in their tracks. Both archetypes combined have a potential 10+ interruptions for your opponent to slog through, while maintaining a superior resource loop - outpacing most other strategies!
 
If you want to win and reach Masters 1 in Masterduel with a relentlessly strong resource-oriented control strategy, you've chosen to pilot the correct deck!

If you want a detailed guide on how to pilot this deck, check out my article from last month.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!


GLHF Duelists!
The main strategy revolves around Synchro summoning and banishing cards. The main Boss is Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying.

The main strategy revolves around flipping up and down your EARTH monsters.

The main bosses are Exxod, Master of The Guard and Subterror Behemoth Fiendess.

deck_excerpt: Theroycrafting a deck so I can play in a locals, but feel free to steal it if you like my ratios!
deck_description:
Do people hate you for playing Runick? Do they call you a "dirty stall player" for playing a deck that generates a lot of advantage while simultaneously trading one for ones with your opponent? Fear not! You can put a healthy dose of burn damage to the mix, so everyone on locals will despise you even more!
Introducing Runick Volcanics. This deck matches the unparalleled card advantage generation and spot removal of Runick, with the control aspect and newfound high burn capabilities of Volcanics to produce a deck that manages to outresource your opponent fast.

Being completely honest, I did not come up with this concept, but these are the ratios I ended up with. I am unsure if I like them or not, and I desperately wanted it to be 40 cards, but basically every Volcanics card is a three-of and 15 is the magic Runick number, so it is very hard to make space for it. You may cut Scattershot if you believe enough on the spot removal of Runick, since Scattershot sucks to draw. Sleipnir is also a possible cut, but I like her :)

Deck is entirely a 1 card combo so it can be crammed with a ton of non-engine and blind second. 1 card combo goes as follows: 

  1. Normal Reich-Heart
  2. Add Arrival
  3. Link Reich-Heart into Light-Heart
  4. Effect - add field spell. 
  5. Activate Field spell to add a Scareclaw or Visas. Whichever works. Any Scareclaw name is best, but Visas does come up as shown in my replays. 
  6. Special the card you added. 
  7. Activate Arrival and special back Reich-Heart. 
  8. Link all 3 into Tri-Heart. 
  9. Bob's your Uncle. You're free to activate Tri-Heart effect which revieves a Scareclaw and searches one then you're 75% of the way to lethal. 

This deck was a super easy climb. The hands it produces are gross. My twitch chat created the meme of "average scareclaw hand" because they look like 3-4 disruptions / board breakers & 1-2 starters more of the time. Of course, there are outliers. Every deck produces some bad hands, occasionally. Good luck if you decide to climb with this deck. It's super fun!

deck_excerpt: Fun combo deck that playes through a surprising amount of interaction, can be used on MD with no additions
deck_description:
This deck is relatively easy to learn the basics of but once you play it more you start to see its potential.

For MD i would replace triple tac with max c

going first I find its weaker thus the deck is more geared towards going second, though the deck can potentially put up an omni and a monster and spell negate under ideal circumstances.

going second it has good potential to OTK but you have to be quite careful with resource management or you could find yourself just off lethal. despite that it can usually play through a fair amount of interaction and set up some negates if you cant OTK.

Extra note about going second: if you think you can get to lethal without it dont use rookie fur hire as it locks you too only attacking with fur hire monsters, worst case senario use it to get too wiz or rafale through beat or something similar.

Extra note in general: the deck is usually pretty good at not bricking but usually you want two different fur hire monsters in hand (ideally 3)

good luck and have fun

deck_description:

Objetivo do Deck é invocar o Obelisco, O Atormentador (tanto na mão como do cemitério), ou acabar com o Deck do Oponente impossibilitando de realizar uma compra.

O deck, funciona como um Mill Deck (Moinho) aonde se enviam as cartas de seu deck para o cemitério e por muitas vezes se enviam as do oponente (você não precisa se preocupar se ficar quase sem cartas, se no caso você tiver em seu controle (campo ou mão) a armadilha Troca de Espírito.

 

O deck também funciona desta forma para que Mudora ganhe um bônus de ataque de todos os monstros fada no cemitério.

Você também pode banir de seu cemitério um Energia da Alma MÁX e puxar um Obelisco, tanto de seu cemitério como de seu Deck para a mão. E caso você não tenha realizado invocações ainda neste turno, você pode usar a mágica Cruzar Almas usando os monstros do oponente como tributo necessário para trazer o Obelisco ao campo.  

Como Ishizu previa o futuro, tendo um monstro fada de terra na mão e Zolga , O Profeta. Você pode invocar o monstro fada de terra no campo, de forma normal e invocar especialmente o Zolga, O Profeta e desta forma ver as 5 primeiras cartas do seu deck e do deck do oponente. Caso você tenha ativo Armadilha do Coveiro, isto desencadeará um combo aonde o seu oponente não conseguirá comprar mais cartas do deck. E caso você tenha a Armadilha do Coveiro e não tenha nenhum Zolga em campo, você pode ativar a mágia Olho Senri  para realizar o mesmo feito.

 

Sempre dê preferencia de ter pelo menos uma Troca de Espírito na mão, e cuide para que o oponente não a venha descartar com o efeito de Arrastado para a Cova.

 

Use os efeitos de ¹Agido, o Sentina Antigo, ²Mudora, o Oráculo da Espada, ³Keldo, a Protetora Sagrada e ºKelbek, a Vangaurda Antiga no seu cemitério para recuperar as melhores cartas do Deck (neste caso não precisa priorizar o Obelisco, porque você tem outras formas de puxar ele)

Se Zolga, o Profeta for tributado para ser invocado pelo seu oponente para trazer um Lava Golem, ou O Dragão Alado de Rá -  Modo Esfera, ou um Kaiju; você pode usar o efeito de Zolga no cemitério destruir o monstro e causar 2000 de dano ao seu oponente.

deck_excerpt: A personal deck to help capture the feeling of playing an old school anime deck in the modern era of Yu-Gi-Oh!
deck_description: It's a bit of a hobby of mine to make, copy, edit, or otherwise think about character decks. Character decks which fit not only the original character's personality and playstyle, but also the vibe, be it the visual aesthetic of the cards, or how well their effects synergize. The typical philosophy is this; only run singles of each card unless you require multiple copies for a particular strategy, use as many cards that character actually used themselves (or a good substitute if the card doesn't exist in the actual game), maintain as much of the original vision, playstyle, and personality as possible, and beyond that just have fun. You're not limited in era so you can run as many retrains or modern support for the pre-existing cards as you want. But that's anime characters, this deck is my own personal character deck, which hopefully encapsulates me as much as possible, it's not meant to be competitive or even particularly good, just something I brainstormed one night while bored and winding down for bed.

This deck is my take on a competitive Tri Spright deck. The idea follows principles from older Tri-brigade formats in which a single card (usually Fraktall) can start a one card Spright Melffy combo all on its own, leaving plenty of room for extra disruption.

Combo 1: Frak sent from hand, dumping kitt then nerv. Player grabs Kerass then normal summons it. Player then specials bearbrum and uses its effect to grab Kitt from banished pile, summoning it to the field. Kerass and Bearbrum are overlayed to make Gigantic which summons Blue which brings Jet, grabbing Doublecross. These two overlay to make Melffy which gets Catty. Kitt's ability is then used to form Double Dragon Lord. Kitt and Melffy are linked to get Sprind, which dumps Angler, which brings two Beaver. The two Beaver are then linked into I:P. On opponent's turn Catty becomes Arch Light and I:P and Sprind can be used to make Gryphon or Apo.

This is the basic combo of the deck and should leave plenty of options to handle opponents' boards. Extra deck monsters fill the side deck to better navigate boards on the draw.

 

Hope everyone enjoys this weird mishmash. :)
Have fun!

deck_excerpt: Machines and burning... good pairing, apparently.
deck_description: As the name of the Deck suggests, this is my take on a modernized and non-archetypical character deck focused around the character Bandit Keith. Mainly this deck exists to burn, banish, or otherwise destroy and disrupt. Cards like Second Coin Toss were added to hopefully portray the sketchy nature of Keith and his tactics, borderline cheating to get the results he wants, while Jackpot 7 exists as the substitute for his 7 Completed Slot Machine play against Joey Wheeler. I didn't want this deck to be too strong, nor did I want it to just go full archetype. I tried to keep the spirit of Keith's original deck alive as much as possible while simply giving it a more modern take that - while definitely not something you wanna bring to a tournament - is at least a fun and usable Deck to use, or at least take notes from for a deck you yourself may be crafting involving a similar idea.

deck_excerpt: Limiter removal level max! All clear! C'mon, T.G. Glaive Blaster!
deck_description:
New T.G. support from AGOV goes so hard. No longer will I need to cope using Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights any longer.

The archetype is still fragile despite the new cards but less T.G. names comes with more engines to use at our disposal such as D/D Savant Kepler which enables us another way to make T.G. Mighty Striker. Diabellestar package is also here as well to bring out T.G. Rocket Salamander which itself is a 1-card combo without having to waste a normal summon. 

Again want to note that the archetype's combos are still fragile so running Crossout Designator may be necessary down the long run. I might also change the ratios on a couple of the T.G. monsters but they seem fine at the moment. Although I'm using some D/D/D cards, I really want to use D/D/D Vice King Requiem so badly because it's funny; however, the extra deck space is rather tight to add D/D/D Deviser King Deus Machinex for a slightly better end board that isn't "towers pass". Also Nibiru, the Primal Being is running rampant at the moment so might as well hold it off for now. All in all fun deck to mess around with and the combos aren't as rigid in contrast to when Crystron Halqifibrax was legal.

ns kepler & activate it's effect to add gate. activate gate and use effect to add vice king requiem. place requiem in the pendulum zone, and activate its effect, sending gate to the gy, and ss itselt, don't change its lv. tribute kepler and requiem for gilgamesh. activate gilgamesh to place savant thomas and orthros in the pendulum zones. activate thomas's effect to add kepler back to hand. use gilgamesh's gained effect(from requiem) to shuffle gate from the gy to the deck and pop thomas. activate kepler into the pendulum zone. pendulum summon thomas and requiem in the zones gilgamesh points to. set wonder xyz/trap trick.use thomas, pop kepler and ss ragnarok from deck. end your turn. in your opponents draw phase, activate wonder xyz/traptrick. if its trap trick, then set wonder xyz, and activate it on the resolution. use wonder xyz, xyz summon kali yuga w/ rangnarok and thomas., locking your opponent out of all card effects. in the end phase of your opponents turn. use kali yuga to destroy all spells/traps on the field. on your turn you can make machinex with your gilgamesh. and this should be enough to attack for game, or combo some more, and then attack for game.

deck_excerpt: Clockwork Night and Duality are incredible tools for Cyber Dragon in Masterduel!
deck_description:
Cyber Dragon has long been a pet deck of mine since forever - I mean, who doesn't like giant serpentine killer robot dragons?! That's such a cool concept for a Yugioh deck! Ever since I've watched GX in my childhood, the machine archetypes of that Yugioh generation have captured my heart - including the Cyber Dragons. However, this archetype has (so far) never reached competitive viability and has always been a mediocre rogue deck.

This changes with the introduction of Masterduel's relatively new secret pack Inherited Unity! This set includes two new cards that are integral and powerful to the Cyber Dragon arsenal - Clockwork Night and Duality!
 
Playing directly with Cyber Dragon's gimmick of contact fusing with opponent's machine monsters, Clockwork Night's fieldwide machine transformation effect suddenly turns Chimeratech Fortress Dragon into a "kaiju" for your opponent's entire board! Clockwork Night's attack boost helps immensely as well, simultaneously boosting all your machine monster's ATK while lowering your opponent's.
 
Duality allows much easier access to Chimeratech Rampage Dragon, furthering your plays with it's double foolish burial and up to whopping 6300ATK points of damage! It can also turn your Fortress and Megafleet Dragon into Cyber Twin Dragon and Cyber End Dragon! 
 
While Cyber Dragon is functionally the same, these two cards further enhance the strategy's ability to break through boards and do what Cyber Dragons do best, OTK with ridiculously high levels of ATK!
 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

ARCHETYPES, ENGINES AND DECKBUILDING

 
This Cyber Dragon deck is played "pure" without any supporting engines. 3 Herz, 3 Core and 3 original Cyber Dragon as well as Cyber Emergency are played, giving the duelist consistent access to a Cyber Dragon name. Along with Clockwork Night, Any one of these monsters contact fuse the opponent's entire board. Triple Herz and Core are played as well, so that they can benefit from Machine Duplication. 1 Cyber Revsystem is included as an additional search target for Core and for extra extension. 
 
1 Regulus is played as an Earth Machine search target for Clockwork Night. Regulus also combos very well with Herz, since it can trigger it's "sent from field to GY" effect. 
 
1 Jizukiru, the Star Destroying Kaiju is played as a board breaking search target for Cyber Repair Plant. It's high 3300ATK shouldn't matter, since it can be contact fused away into Fortress Dragon because it's a machine. 
 
9 handtraps are played as well as the "Maxx C" package of Crossout and Called By the Grave to slow down your opponent and to help enable OTKs happen more easily. 
 
The Extra Deck is designed to compliment Duality's ability to turn monster on the field into their Light/Dark counterpart. Cyber Dragon -> Rampage Dragon, Fortress Dragon -> Cyber Twin Dragon, Megafleet Dragon -> Cyber End Dragon. Duality can also dodge any sort of targeting interruption your opponent has!
 
The deck is 40 cards so that it is as consistent as possible to help facilitate what it's designed to do - OTK going second. 

 

COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN

 

Blind Second Cyber Dragon has one strategy - go second, obliterate an opponent's board and OTK! Here are some classic Cyber Dragon combos: 

 

Cyber Dragon Core + Galaxy Soldier = 9500ATK, Omni-negate, destroy up to two spells/traps. 
  1. Normal summon Cyber Dragon Core. Activate Core's effect to search for Cyber Emergency. 
  2. Activate Cyber Emergency to search for Cyber Dragon Herz. 
  3. Link away Core for Almiraj. Link away Almiraj for Secure Gardna. (Alternatively, if you have Clockwork Night, contact fuse your opponent's board away)!
  4. Activate Galaxy Soldier's effect to summon itself, sending Herz. 
  5. CL1 Herz to search for Cyber Dragon, CL2 Galaxy Soldier to search for another Galaxy Soldier. 
  6. Activate Galaxy Soldier's effect to summon itself, sending Cyber Dragon. 
  7. XYZ summon Cyber Dragon Nova using Galaxy Soldier + Galaxy Soldier. 
  8. Activate Nova's effect to summon Cyber Dragon from GY. 
  9. Overlay Cyber Dragon Infinity on top of Nova. If opponent still has a monster on-field, activate Infinity's effect to attach their monster as material. 
  10. Link summon Predaplant Anaconda using Cyber Dragon + Secure Gardna. 
  11. Activate Anaconda's effect, copying Overload Fusion's effect. Fusion summon Chimeratech Rampage Dragon, banishing from GY Cyber Dragon and Herz as material. 
  12. On summon, Rampage Dragon destroy up to two spells/traps on your opponent's field.
  13. Activate Rampage Dragon's effect to send to GY two light machines to GY so it can attack 3 times. 
  14. Enter battle phase, and you have a total of 9500ATK on board to OTK with (Rampage -  6300ATK, Infinity - 2700ATK, Anaconda - 500ATK). 

 This same combo can be done if you have Cyber Dragon Core + Herz. Instead of searching Cyber Emergency with Core, search Cyber Repair Plant. Link away Core so that it goes into the GY, and Cyber Repair Plant searches for Galaxy Soldier! 

 

Cyber Dragon Core/Herz + Machine Duplication = 9500ATK, Omni-negate, destroy up to two spells/traps. 

 

  1. Normal summon Cyber Dragon Core/Herz. if you summoned Core, search for your "Cyber" spell of choice. (Emergency for another search, Repair Plant to search for Kaiju, Revsystem for extension).
  2. Activate Machine Duplication targeting Core/Herz, summoning 2 Cyber Dragon from deck. 
  3. Link away Core for Almiraj. Link away Almiraj for Secure Gardna. (Alternatively, if you have Clockwork Night, contact fuse your opponent's board away)!
  4. XYZ summon Cyber Dragon Nova using Cyber Dragon + Cyber Dragon. 
  5. Repeat steps 9 -> 14 detailed above. 

 

This is another variant of the combo with the same end result, but with Machine Duplication. 

 

GENERAL TIPS

  • Clear the board first, then go for full Cyber Dragon combo to OTK! It's very difficult to OTK if you're interrupted at any point. 
  • If your opponent targets your Cyber Dragons for any effect, you can dodge them using Duality while summoning a powerful monster from Extra Deck!
  • Clockwork Night is excellent bait for your opponent to negate. If they don't remove it from the field and you have a Cyber Dragon on board, their whole field will be contact fused away!
  • Many handtraps are included in this deck to simplify your opponent's boardstate making them easier to OTK. Be sure to time your handtraps properly to weaken your opponent!
  • If your opponent Maxx C's you while you're trying to combo, just keep going and go all-in on OTK! All the cards won't matter if their lifepoints are 0.
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 

CONCLUDING COMMENTARY

 

Cyber Dragon, one of the coolest machine decks ever has got a great boost with Duality and Clockwork Night! Contact fusing your opponent's entire board feels incredibly good and satisfying while generating advantage and firepower with Duality streamlines Cyber Dragon into another level!
 
While Cyber Dragon isn't competitively viable (it's only rogue for now), if piloted correctly it can win consistently vs. top decks on Masterduel Ladder.
 
GLHF Duelists!
